/*
given a tree of N node, N-1 edges; rootes at node 1.
each note is assigned wither 1 or 0;
for each node i, find the number of 1's on the
shortest path from node 1 to node i.



first of all,
in a tree there is exactly one simple path between any 2 nodes.
because tree has:
connected, no cycle, n nodes, n-1 edges
if there were 2 diff. path b/w same nodes then that would create a cycle
but tree is acyclic.
so only one path is possible, and that is only the shortest path.


so we will reframe the question:
Given a Tree of ‘N’ Nodes and ‘N-1’ Edges; rooted at Node-1 ;
each node is assigned either 1 or 0 ; for each node “i” ;
find the number of 1’s from node 1 to node “i”.



eg:
            (0)1
            /  \
        (1)2  (0)3
              /   \
            (1)4  (1)5

so
t[1]=0 //no. of 1's from 1 to 1
t[2]=1 //no. of 1's from 1 to 2
t[3]=0 //no. of 1's from 1 to 3
t[4]=1 //no. of 1's from 1 to 4
t[5]=1 //no. of 1's from 1 to 5

so there is a trick for future questions:

VERY IMPORTANT
think that a tree is an array.
eg:
    1(0)
    |
    2(1)
    |
    3(1)
    |
    4(0)


now solve that like an array. it will be easy
now traverse it

when we are at 1,
so no.of 1's --> 0
when at 2, total 1's= prefix sum + current value --> 0+1
when at 3, total= 2
when at 4, total= 2

so at each node we are basically adding the old sum + current value.
same thing we can do with our tree.




*/

import java.util.*;

public class _02_google_interview_question {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        int nodes = sc.nextInt();
        int edges = sc.nextInt();

        ArrayList<Integer>[] arr = new ArrayList[nodes + 1];

        int[] val=new int[nodes+1];

        for (int i = 1; i <= nodes; i++) {
            val[i]=sc.nextInt();
            arr[i] = new ArrayList<>();
        }

        for (int i = 1; i <= edges; i++) {
            int x = sc.nextInt();
            int y = sc.nextInt();

            arr[x].add(y);
            arr[y].add(x);

        }

        findNoOfOne(arr, 1, nodes,val);
    }

    static void findNoOfOne(ArrayList<Integer>[] arr, int src, int nodes,int[] val) {
        Queue<Integer> q = new LinkedList<>();
        int[] visited=new int[nodes+1];
        int[] answer = new int[nodes + 1];

        q.add(src);
        visited[src]=1;
        answer[src]=val[src];

        while (!q.isEmpty()){
            int node=q.poll();

            for(int i:arr[node]){
                if (visited[i]==0){
                    answer[i]=answer[node]+val[i];
                    q.add(i);
                    visited[i]=1;
                }

            }
        }
        for(int i=1;i<=nodes;i++){
            System.out.println(answer[i]);
        }
    }
}
